Week 2: OPP, Error handling, File I/O
This Week: Understanding of Class, Objects, Attributes, Methods, Inheritance, Polymorphism, encapsulation, Exception handling, File I/O
Class : It holds all kinds of objects, methods and attributes, it is the main thing for your code where everything is organized.
Objects : It is mainly seen as real time memory like if you enter something it directly goes into your storage and sits there.
Attribute : These are the things where you define the values that belongs to an object
Method : It is an action that an object can perform

Employee (Class)
|
|- defines:
|     name
|     age
|     salary
|     work()
|
|----------------
|               |
v               v

emp1            emp2
|               |
|- name         |- name
|- age          |- age
|- salary       |- salary
|- work()       |- work()

here
1. Employee - class
2. Name of the emp1 ex: Deepak - object (data gets stores)
3. name age salary -  attributes
4. work() - method (if it is independent of class it is function)

xxxx------------------------------------------------------------------------xxxx

Encapsulation : Object is responsible for protecting and managing its own data
    Ex : Designing UI in such a way that making user to take action rather than they are changing the code for their own use
    why : to protect the data and ensure the changes are done only by valid operations
Abstraction : showing what someone can do or what kind of actions are taken not how it is done (like showing the UI rather than the allocation of memory etc.)
    Ex : if you have to append a number you see the number appended but in background the memory allocation, array resizing are not shown but they are done, the part which is not shown is due to the code follows the abstraction
    why: to hide complex parts and show cleaner UI
Inheritance : Creating new class with the help of existing class in order to avoid the duplication of code
    Ex : create a clas of employee and can use that class in Developer, Engineer, Manager where the roles are different, the inner actions are different but the data for basic information is same
    why : to reuse the code to avoid the duplication
Polymorphism : Different objects responds to same method call in their own way
    Ex : for an employee you ask what is his role some say they are managers, some says they are engineers some says they are developers but at the end they are employees
    why : to write the code that works with many objects in their own way

Employee
| salary * commission
|-- Developer (salary * commission_1)
|-- Engineer (salary * commission_2)
|-- Manager (salary * commission_3)

here
1. Developer, Engineer, Manager uses same employee code - inheritance
2. If the commission of manager cannot be changed by engineer or while changing the commission of manager engineer's commission cannot be changed - encapsulation
3. the salary * commission class is used by all the employees but the calculations internally is different- polymorphism

xxxx------------------------------------------------------------------------xxxx

Exception : The code couldn't do what we ask, it is not a bug, not always a programming mistake, sometime user mistake, or network failure etc.
Exception Handling :
    1. Try : It means I am going to attempt this
    2. Except : if something goes wrong in try, the code comes to here, there can be multiple exceptions, and in exception we can add else like something in exception doesn't match goes to else
    3. Finally : No matter what executes or what not executes it goes from finally,  it means that a code goes from try and if we have finally, anything written in that will also be executed same along with except

Example :
    try:                                    # tries this code
        customer = get_customer()
        invoice = create_invoice(customer)
        save_invoice(invoice)

    except DatabaseError:                   # if there is a connection error
        print("Database unavailable.")

    except FileNotFoundError:               # if there is an error in file fetching
        print("Template missing.")

    finally:                                # it executes no matter what
        disconnect_database()

xxxx------------------------------------------------------------------------xxxx

File I/0 : Imagine doing work with a data in a file, so python has a feature for using file data directly like :
    1. Opening a File : It is accessing a file
    2. Reading a File : After getting the access we can read the file
    2.1 : Reading 1 line in a file :
    if there are 3 entries for example
            Deepak
            Rahul
            priya

         Ex: with open("employees.txt") as file:
                print(file.readline())
         output :
         > Deepak
         call again
         > Rahul

    2.2 : Reading all lines :
        Ex : with open("employee.txt") as file
                lines = file.readlines()
        output :
        [
        'Deepak\n',
        'Rahul\n',
        'Priya\n'
        ]
    3. Closing a File : Every file opening will takes memory, File gets locked, and program slows so we need to close a file which we opened

    Ex :
        file = open("employees.txt")   # access/Opens a file
        print(file.read())             # reads a file and prints
        file.close()                   # Closes file after its use

    Ex : In a professional way - here as the block ends, the file automatically closes
            with open("employees.txt") as file :
                print(file.read())                  #here no need for close()

    4. Writing a file : it creates a new file or replaces the existing ones
            with  open(employees.txt,"w") as file:
                file.write("Janaki")
       file becomes : Janaki           # even it there is a content, it overwrites
    4.1. Append : It will add anything at the end
            with  open(employees.txt,"a") as file :
                file.write("\nRam")
        file becomes : Janaki
                       Ram

    Modes :
    r  Read only
    w  Write only
    a  Append
    r+ Read and write
    w+ Write and read
    a+ Append and read

